<section id="secfhsst_id1106"><title> Mathematical Description of Waves </title>
      <para id="id321658">If you look carefully at the pictures of waves you will notice that they look very much like <emphasis effect="italics">sine</emphasis> or <emphasis effect="italics">cosine</emphasis> functions. This is correct. Waves can be described by
trigonometric functions that are functions of time or of position.
Depending on which case we are dealing with the function will be a
function of <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi>t</m:mi></m:math> or <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:math>.
For example, a function of position would be:</para>
      <equation id="id321696">
        <m:math overflow="scroll" mode="display">
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mi>y</m:mi>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mo>(</m:mo>
              <m:mi>x</m:mi>
              <m:mo>)</m:mo>
            </m:mrow>
            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
            <m:mi>A</m:mi>
            <m:mo form="prefix">sin</m:mo>
            <m:mfenced separators="" open="(" close=")">
              <m:msup>
                <m:mn>360</m:mn>
                <m:mo>∘</m:mo>
              </m:msup>
              <m:mfrac>
                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                <m:mi>λ</m:mi>
              </m:mfrac>
              <m:mo>+</m:mo>
              <m:mi>φ</m:mi>
            </m:mfenced>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:math>
      </equation>
      <para id="id321750">where <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi>A</m:mi></m:math> is the amplitude, <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi>λ</m:mi></m:math> the wavelength and <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi>φ</m:mi></m:math> is a <emphasis effect="italics">phase shift</emphasis>. The phase shift accounts for the fact that the wave at <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math> does not start at the equilibrium position.
A function of time would be:</para>
      <equation id="id321804">
        <m:math overflow="scroll" mode="display">
          <m:mrow>
            <m:mi>y</m:mi>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mo>(</m:mo>
              <m:mi>t</m:mi>
              <m:mo>)</m:mo>
            </m:mrow>
            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
            <m:mi>A</m:mi>
            <m:mo form="prefix">sin</m:mo>
            <m:mfenced separators="" open="(" close=")">
              <m:msup>
                <m:mn>360</m:mn>
                <m:mo>∘</m:mo>
              </m:msup>
              <m:mfrac>
                <m:mi>t</m:mi>
                <m:mi>T</m:mi>
              </m:mfrac>
              <m:mo>+</m:mo>
              <m:mi>φ</m:mi>
            </m:mfenced>
          </m:mrow>
        </m:math>
      </equation>
      <para id="id321857">where <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi>T</m:mi></m:math> is the period of the wave.
Descriptions of the wave incorporate the amplitude, wavelength, frequency or period and a phase shift. </para>
</section>
